{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614496"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16367"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16367"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0,0.8,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9058"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114429"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9058"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16367"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96430"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"5933"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7196"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21537"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21540"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22741"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114429"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA key function of the extraocular muscles is to maintain alignment of the eyes to enable single binocular vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHorizontal diplopia can result from damage to a particular cranial nerve.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Damage to which one of the following cranial nerves, might lead to these symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trochlear nerve (cranial nerve IV)","Trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V)","Abducens nerve (cranial nerve VI)","Facial nerve (cranial nerve VII)","Vestibulocochlear nerve (cranial nerve VIII)"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabducens nerve (cranial nerve VI)\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the lateral rectus muscle, which is responsible for abducting the eye (moving it laterally). When this nerve is damaged, the affected eye cannot abduct properly and drifts medially, resulting in horizontal diplopia that worsens on lateral gaze. This patient has been asked to look to the left and is unable to move her left eye laterally - causing horizontal diplopia (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory innervation to the face and motor supply to muscles of mastication. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E controls facial expression muscles and has no direct role in eye movement. The \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibulocochlear nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for hearing and balance. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etrochlear nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the superior oblique muscle and when damaged causes vertical rather than horizontal diplopia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHorizontal diplopia occurs when the eyes are misaligned in the horizontal plane, most commonly due to weakness of the lateral rectus (cranial nerve VI) or medial rectus (cranial nerve III) muscles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cranial nerve VI (abducens nerve) innervates the lateral rectus muscle which abducts the eye.","Damage to cranial nerve VI causes medial deviation of the affected eye and horizontal diplopia.","Horizontal diplopia occurs when the eyes are misaligned in the horizontal plane due to weakness of the lateral or medial rectus muscles."],"references":["Jain S. Diplopia: Diagnosis and management. Clin Med (Lond). 2022 Mar;22(2):104-106. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2022-0045. PMID: 35304368; PMCID: PMC8966821","Dinkin M. Diagnostic approach to diplopia. Continuum (Minneap Minn). 2014 Aug;20(4 Neuro-ophthalmology):942-65. doi: 10.1212/01.CON.0000453310.52390.58. PMID: 25099102; PMCID: PMC10563939","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96430"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16367"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21294"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21294"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/msQLefbjDTwUdrBJN0pZA15XSjxgoY.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/msQLefbjDTwUdrBJN0pZA15XSjxgoY.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1009}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96430"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-16T17:01:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-16T17:01:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9058"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114429"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attrib